SYMPTOM_TEXT: 12 y.o. male patient with history of developmental delay, seizure disorder who presented to the emergency department today with acute encephalopathy, unresponsive with bradycardia,  V-tach requiring defibrillation, and acute respiratory failure requiring intubation.  The family had been traveling and vacationing with extended family members and recently returned Saturday night. No sick contacts during the trip and he recently received his second COVID-19 vaccine on June 5th.  On Sunday, June 20th, he had cold symptoms with stuffy nose, sneezing and minimal oral intake. Mother gave him 10ml of a multi-symptom OTC cold medication that evening.  Unsure what is in the medication or if it contains Benadryl.  This morning, he had an 11am swim lesion and then came back and slept on the couch.  Still minimal oral intake and was resting all day long but awake most of the time.  This evening at 5:43pm per mother, he received another 10ml of the multi-symptom cold medication. He was given his Vimpat and Valproic Acid medications around 7:30pm.  Around 8:20/8:25pm, he was asleep and had an emesis and was not responding In the ED, he was unresponsive and poor respiratory effort with episodes of apnea and was incontient of stool during the exam.  He was brought to the resuscitation room, PIV placed x2.  Placed on oxygen initially. Ativan given once for possible seizure. Epinephrine given for bradycardia.  Noted V-tach on rhythm.  Second Epi given, started Epinephrine infusion and Shock given 2J/kg.  Cardiology at bedside.   Rocuronium and Etomidate given for intubation.  He was intubated on the second attempt with 6.0c ETT.

So the day after my vaccine, in the morning, I was so exhausted and felt horrible I had a temperature of around 101. I was just like so tired and loss my sense of smell and taste. This all slowly started and as the days went on I also experienced blurry vision and brain fog and swelling in my joints. For about the first three weeks after my injection I was literally in bed. I took unpaid leave because I just could not work and I maxed out my leave. I have a 2 and a 6 year old and it was just so painful that I could not move or get out of bed much. The pain in my body was horrible. After I lost my senses on that Monday, on May 3rd 2021 I went to get a Covid test and sure enough it came back positive on the rapid test. The fatigue is debilitating and I am still not working. On May 12 2021 I went to the ER for chest tightness, shortness of breath and fatigue, my oxygen levels were low. The ER DR took me off work for another week and then I ended up seeing my PCD on I think May 18th 2021, she ordered speech and physically therapy for me. PEM (protein-energy malnutrition) is what she diagnosed me with, specific to Covid-19. I am now on FMLA leave and that started on I think the 12th or the 18th of May 2021, this really messed me up with my memory and stuff so I am not sure. I have 8 weeks of physical therapy scheduled once per week. I was also referred to a Cardiologist. I saw a nutritionist on June 9th 2021 because I gained weight due to being in bed long term. They started me on an anti-inflammatory diet. On June 10 2021 I saw a speech therapist. I was supposed to return June 18th 2021 but I could not begin again. I am only allowed to worked one day per week right now and am supposed to start on Friday. On July 14th 2021 I also have another cardiologist appointment scheduled.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the vaccine at approximately 10am on 6/21/21. Shortly after receiving the vaccine, he complained of a headache and arm pain. Patient was told to remain seated and was monitored by pharmacist and staff. After 20 minutes, he was still not feeling well. He was moved into a different observation area. Based on symptoms it appeared he was having a a vasovagal reaction. He did not want to lie down and elevate his feet. At approximately 1/2 hour, he became nauseous and threw up. We continued to monitor him. He still had a headache and said he felt off. He had no swelling in the face and was speaking without issue. No hives were noticed. Patient said he was having a hard time breathing- I suggested he remove his mask to get more fresh air. After removing the mask, he said it felt better to breathe. In total, patient was monitored for 3 hours. He did not lose conscience, exhibit facial swelling or hives.  Patient went back to work for 1 hour then left to go home.  Prior to receiving the shot, patient showed a lot of anxiety and was hesitant to get vaccine. In the end, he decided he wanted to get it. Per medical staff at his work, he does tend to be high stressed and anxious. I followed up with patient on 6/22/21. He stated that he was feeling a lot better. He did have redness at the injection site- I explained he could ice the area. He still had a headache= I instructed him he could take a pain reliever. He mentioned he had a purple spot on his back. I asked if he had any other spots and said he would have to check. I suggested he contact his PCP and make an appointment to be seen.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 14 y.o. male with no significant PMHx who presented on 6/7 with substernal chest pain, SOB, and diaphoresis. Chest pain while he was in class and progressively worsened, was substernal and was not affected by position. Rated pain as 7/10. He also had associated diaphoresis and SOB. He reported to his school nurse who sent him to the ED. Denies palpitations, no syncope or LOC. No trauma to his chest. No palpitations. No family history of cardiac disease. Denies fever. He plays basketball, football and bassbal but reports he had not participated in any sports after he got the second dose of the vaccine. No similar history of chest pain in the past. No history of syncope. Of note, he received the second dose of the Pfizer COVID vaccine on 6/4. He had received the first dose 3 weeks earlier.    In the ED he was noted to be afebrile, PR of 64, RR of 18 and BP of 117/71. His SpO2 was 98% on room air. His Troponin T was 0.04 and BNP was <50. CRP was 10.3, Ferritin, 64 and had a reassuring CBC. Chest XR with no evidence of a cardiopulmonary process. His EKG showed borderline ST elevation in lead II.    Pedi ID consulted for acute myocarditis in the setting of completed Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine. Echo on 6/8 showed normal cardiac anatomy and normal biventricular function. Repeat EKG on 6/8 was normal. Troponin T on 6/8 increased to 0.16. His CRP today is down to 7.3. His COVID-19 nasopharyngeal PCR is negative but SARS-CoV-2 nucleocapsid antibody and SARS-CoV-2 spike protein antibody were both positive. No known history of COVID-19 infection in patient or family members. RVP is negative. CMV serology is negative but other infectious diseases work up are pending. UA without pyuria. He has received IVIG and now  on steroid.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The pt had his first Moderna covid vaccine on 3/19, and after the vaccination, he developed left upper lateral calf pain that lasted several weeks.  He then had his second Moderna covid vaccine on 4/22, with left knee pain, and again left upper lateral proximal calf pain.  He denies any chest pain, heaviness, tightness, pressure, palpitations, or dizziness.  He contacted his PCP, and he was advised to come to the ER for evaluation of a possible DVT.   This is very suspicious for a direct thrombotic side effect of the pt's Moderna vaccine.  The pt has a very high d-dimer, and we can not rule out a mid-distal thigh and left popliteal DVT, so the pt will be covered with Lovenox, and he will present to hospital tomorrow to obtain a venous duplex.  They can then, based on clot burden and his subsequent complaints on continuing lovenox bridge to warfarin or a direct acting anticoagulant.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 1620, pt. received Pfizer vaccine administered by RN at clinic. Pt. was sent to observation area, which is in the cafeteria. During assessment, pt. was found diaphoretic, pale in skin color, pt. reported blurry vision, and trouble breathing. Pt. respirations rate was 16 breaths per minute, non-labored, no signs of any distress. Pt. stated no prior medical history. After a few minutes, pt. started to recover. Pt. skin color started to improve and less diaphoretic. At 1629, EMS called by RN. Pt was moved to another area away from other patients. Pt. was able to ambulate, follow commands/ directions without any deficits. At 1637, EMS arrived, pt. vitals was taken BP=100/50's and stable. Pt. refused to go to the hospital for further observation. RN stayed with pt. until 1700. Pt. was given some snacks and drinks (gatorade and water). Pt. was moved across the nurses' vaccination table for further monitoring. Pt. fully recovered and left to go home at 1732.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within an hour of vaccine receipt, patient noted increased thirst with dry mouth and lips. She increased her water intake over the next 48 hours. Around 4 Apr, she noted cracking at the corners of her mouth. During that time, she applied lip balm and Chapstick to her lips almost constantly, with Neosporin applied to the areas cracking.  The following week (week of 5 Apr), she noted her labia were itchy and irritated; she denies vaginal irritation or discharge. No abdominal or pelvic pain. She applied an antifungal cream to the area with some relief of symptoms.  Also that week (week of 5 Apr), patient had itching and dry, flaking skin in her external ears; no discharge or pain from inner ear. She also noted that her taste buds were enlarged and red; they were irritated and they burned if she ate spicy food.  The following week (week of 12 Apr), patient noted her scalp was itching and flaking, so she started using Selsun shampoo. Then, her hands became very dry and itchy, and began to peel. Her feet developed small, itchy vesicles that dried and then peeled.  Patient attempted to be evaluated, but the first available face-to-face appointment was not until 3 May. At that time, exam of her skin noted:  macule seen on Palms of b/l hands- macular scaly lesions that are peeling.  b/l feet (near arch, lateral surface) small macular lesions w/o ulceration, nonvesicular nor pustular.  R corner of mouth- with small crack, no erythema or discharge.  - Scales were seen. Assessment/Plan: 1. Dermatitis, unspecified: Suspect flare of Atopic dermatitis.  2. Other specified disorders of the skin and subcutaneous tissue: Suspect angular chelitis of R corner of mouth She was prescribed Fluocinonide 0.05% and Ceramide creams to apply to her hands and feet. Mupirocin 2% ointment ((apply to lips) and Clotrimazole 1% vaginal cream were also prescribed.  Patient denies onset of facial swelling, swelling and itching of mouth and throat, difficulty swallowing or breathing, wheezing, watery eyes, cough, increased heart rate, lightheadedness, and GI-symptoms within the first 12 hours post-vaccine receipt.   Patient was feeling well on the day of vaccine receipt and denies any other possible exposures, including changes in foods and medications, and personal care products. She denies bug/insect bites, chemical exposure, exposure to plants, and exposures to sick contacts. She reports a negative health history for chronic or long-standing health conditions, except for a history of Atopic Dermatitis, with her last flare about 10 years ago. Patient also reports receipt of lip fillers 4 to 5 years ago. She denies a history of COVID infection; she has tested negative 3 times for SARS-CoV-2.  Recently, patient reports increased stressors and just initiated Bupropion. Otherwise, she takes no routine medications. She has a Mirena IUD. She has no known allergies to medication, food, latex, or insect stings.  Patient denies previous history of reactions following vaccine receipt. She has no history of similar rashes or dermatitis, except peeling of skin on hands and feet are similar to flares of atopic dermatitis).  Patient works as a dental hygienist. On 18 May, patient had noted near resolution of all oral-facial symptoms. Her other cutaneous symptoms had improved significantly, but she was still reporting pruritus of the scalp, feet, and hands. She had just initiated a Medrol Dosepak, Atarax, and Ketoconazole shampoo.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The date of the second dose was 05/25/2021, which is when the side effects started. I had the normal and expected effects, such as a sore arm and fatigue. I began my period that morning, before I went in for the shot. I would like to be as detailed as possible, so I will likely include some graphic details in this description. My apologies in advance.  My period normally lasts 3-4 days and is moderate (as far as I know) regarding blood loss. After the second dose, the flow was extremely heavy and my period lasted for almost an entire week (7 days). It was miserable. I was bloated and tender in that area, and extremely tired. I was also cramping, which is unusual for me nowadays.  About two weeks after that, I felt a stabbing or ripping pain in the uterus area. It stayed for about two days, throbbing every minute or so. I could not sleep those days. It was not so unbearable that I could not perform everyday actions, but it was taking up a good portion of my thoughts that weekend. After that, it went away and I thought it was over.  About three days ago from today (today is June 22nd, or 06/22/2021), the pain returned and I knew it meant the start of my period. The timing was normal. The next day I began bleeding, but the flow is again much heavier than normal. The pain is back and much worse than before. I am going through many more pads than usual and it is, for me, a worrying amount of blood. Since this is the second period in a row I am experiencing this, I felt it was necessary to report it in. I hope this is okay and not taking resources from those with worse issues.  I would also like to note that I experienced my first panic attack in 5 years the night of my second dose (for no reason- they've always had a concrete reason for occurring) and my anxiety was notably worse that week (I am on medication and was otherwise doing very well managing the anxiety). During the attack I experienced the usual symptoms: my throat closing up and making it harder to breathe, and uncontrollable shaking and crying.  I was not thinking of anything that would make me nervous at the time of the attack. I had just finished an online gaming session with a friend and was showering to prepare for bed, so I was fully relaxed.  Additionally, my mental health has notably dipped a bit over the last month, though there are a number of factors at play and I don't want to blame the vaccine for that. However, I was told to at least make note of it here just in case there does end up being a correlation.
OTHER_MEDS: Prescribed Prozac and Concerta. I also take Vitamin D supplements since I don't go outside as much as I'd like.
HISTORY: I am diagnosed with anxiety, depression, and ADHD, which is why I'm on Concerta and Prozac. Otherwise, I have no physical health conditions I'm aware of.

LAB_DATA: On 6/20/2021 she had a normal CT of the head, negative comprehensive drug screen, LP with elevated opening pressure of 34, CSF protein elevated at 270, CSF RBC 700, CSF glucose 51 and CSF WBC 910 (84 segmented neutrophils, 6 lymphocytes and 10 monocytes). The CSF was sent for several studies including HSV PCR (negative), Enterovirus PCR (uninterpretable due to interfering substance), CMV PCR, EBV PCR, HHV-6 PCR, Lyme antibody, West Nile antibodies, Arbovirus panel, and Jamestown Canyon Virus. She had a partial MRI on 06/20/2021 because of patient motion but it showed "Nonspecific restricted diffusion in the centrum semiovale and corpus callosum. These findings at the corpus callosum in have been described with cytotoxic edema secondary to multiple etiologies. Differential considerations include, but not limited to, bacterial and viral infectious processes and toxic/metabolic etiologies." An MRI done on 6/21/2021 showed " Interval decrease in the extent of the cytotoxic lesion of the corpus callosum posteriorly. There is been resolution of involvement in the deep white matter. Differential remains unchanged. There are no other interval changes." The MRA/MRV was normal. The EEG on 06/20/2021 showed "This routine awake and sleep EEG is abnormal due to following: - Poor or lack of common background organization, diffuse background slowing, poorly sustained posterior dominant rhythm and/or sleep architecture, suggestive of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, or encephalopathy, nonspecific to etiology. - Focal slowing noted in bilateral frontal areas, suggestive of underlying focal cerebral dysfunction in the above head region(s). No seizures were recorded during the study."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: As Medical Lead I had previously consulted Dr.  on this patient 4/27/2021 due to patient called  Public Health with concerns regarding receiving COVID-19 vaccine. Patient had suffered a shingles outbreak 3/27/2021 and wanted to know if she should follow through with receiving COVID vaccination on her scheduled appointment date 4/30/2021. Patient reported at that time that her shingles had ?mostly cleared up?. This Medical Lead RN informed patient that I had seen no data contraindicating receipt of Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine by this patient, but due to her concerns I would consult our Health Department Physician. After review of medical history as described by this patient with Dr.  and review of data and guidelines from CDC website and Pfizer website  patient was informed by myself that there is no  contraindication to receiving the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine after a shingles outbreak. Patient reported she had completed acyclovir and prednisone treatments for shingles and that she had not had shingles prior to her 3/27/21 outbreak.  On 5/20/2021 pt called  Public Health with concerns about perceived possible side effects. As Medical Lead I again returned the call and spoke with  pt. Patient reports she is currently experiencing ?calf pain in both legs and in her right leg the pain goes all the way up to her hip?. Patient reports that immediately after receiving Pfizer injection 4/30/2021 (while in observation) she ?felt electric shocks on my lower legs that started on the bottom of my feet? and also stated ?I didn?t tell anybody? (at the vaccination site). This Medical Lead RN informed patient that the purpose of the Observation Station at vaccination site is for patients to report any side effects or adverse reactions  immediately following vaccination. This Medical Lead RN went on to inform patient that these signs and symptoms which she was just now reporting are not side effects that have been reported with the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine and that she should follow up with her primary care physician. Patient stated she has been to Urgent Care twice and seen a Dermatologist regarding her symptoms. I disclosed to this patient that I am not a physician, but I am interested in discussing her concerns so that I may assist her within my scope of practice.    Patient went on to report she suffered vomiting, diarrhea, and elevated temperature within approximately 48 hours of vaccination and resolved shortly thereafter.  This Medical Lead RN informed patient that vomiting, diarrhea, and elevated temperature are indeed documented and known side effects which have been reported with the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine.   Patient went on to report ?Everything got worse after the vaccination. Now I have bumps below my earlobes and near my hair line on both sides. The largest and most painful is along my jawline?. Patient reports that prior to vaccination, her shingles were ?mostly cleared up? and she ?went ahead and got the vaccination?. Patient reports she went to Urgent Care due to ?left shoulder pain that went all the way to my heart? and complaints of persistent shingles. During that Urgent Care visit Patient states she received a second prescription for acyclovir (treatment nearly complete) and ?cream?. Patient states she was seen by a dermatologist who prescribed Prednisolone but ?nobody tested the fluid? (from shingles blisters).
LAB_DATA: This RN has no access to medical tests and laboratory results. Client states she has been seen at  Urgent Care on 2 separate occasions and at  Dermatology  prior to our 5/20/2021 phone conversation. Client did follow up with, NP,  Health Clinic  for ongoing symptoms.
OTHER_MEDS: Hydromorphone 4mg daily and Diazepam regularly. Uses Benadryl 25mg, 1-2 tabs, regularly. Client states she mad a VAERS report herself by telephone prior to my interview 5/20/2021. Client stated she had been treated for shingles with acyclov
HISTORY: Client reports having been electrocuted at  Physical Therapy, and sustained spinal injury from a car accident. Client states she has been in several car accidents, states she was placed on several different meds which didn't work.
ALLERGIES: Client states she is allergic to Gabapentin, Baclofen, latex, eggs and egg products.

The patient is a very pleasant 43-year-old female with morbid obesity (167 kilos at 5 foot 6 inches height) and asthma.  She is without a prior cardiac history.  She has been under significant emotional stress after the unexpected death of her husband approximately 2 weeks ago.  She remained medically well, however, until approximately midnight this morning, 06/13/21, when she developed acute onset of chest discomfort at rest.  These symptoms were sufficiently severe such that the paramedics were summoned.  Her EKG en route was suggestive of anterior ST-segment elevation.  However, upon her arrival, her presenting EKG was without significant ST segment changes.  Despite the latter and despite aggressive medical therapy, including high-dose heparin, aspirin and Brilinta, at 0215 hours, she developed recurrent severe chest discomfort, as well as new anterior ST-segment elevation on her EKG.    In summary, the patient presented with an evolving anterior ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction diagnosed by qualifying EKG at 0215 hours.  For this, she underwent successful thrombectomy, angioplasty, and drug-eluting stenting with excellent result both by angiography and by optical imaging.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 69-year-old female with past medical history of coronary artery disease status post double bypass on May 2015, hypertension, hyperlipidemia came to emergency room with chief complaint of chest pain going on since Wednesday.  She says that initially the pain started after she ate her food and she has history of gallbladder polyp and hence she thought it might be her gallbladder and indigestion and took Tums.  Pain was associated with nausea at that time.  Her pain recurred next day after eating and she took nitroglycerin after which she felt better. A 26-year-old man with no PMH presented to our hospital with a meningitis-like illness (4/18/2021) about 4-6 weeks after receiving both doses of the Pfizer COVID vaccine. Chief complaints on admission included excessive fatigue, nuchal rigidty, fevers, and, headache, and some confusion. He also had a rash on his L forehead 2 weeks prior to admission that resolved after taking ibuprofen, however this is unlikely to have treated this rash.   With the working diagnosis of meningitis/enecephalitis, the patient received Acyclovir (4/18?4/21), ampicillin (4/19), ceftriaxone (4/18?4/22), and vancomycin (4/18?4/19) initiated. All labs (will document below) and patient was discharged on a 14 days course of doxycycline 100mg PO BID to cover empirically for possible Lyme meningitis vs. Leptospirosis.   On outpatient follow-up visits, patient reported appropriate adherence to doxycycline, no sick contacts, no further rashes, no fevers, chills, headaches, photophobia/phonophobia, etc.  Does not seem to have any lasting sequelae from "meningitis-like illness."

The nurse hotline called us back as we couldn't get through and stated we should definitely be seen at Urgent Care. We walked into urgent care, and they refused to see us and directed us to the Emergency Room if we felt it "necessary" Since our 4 yr old had a 105.2 fever and we were scared AND had been told to be concerned if it reached over 105.0, we ran over to ER. We were seen and axillary temperatures were taken about 3 different times which were around 102.0. I asked for a temperature under her tongue since I know that axillary temperatures aren't too accurate. By that time, her fever had come down to about 100.0 I think (we had been waiting there for an hour I believe so far) and were told by the doctor that it was normal and she was fine. I asked for a social worker or someone to help us navigate the process of somehow trying to get an exemption for the MMR vaccine to which she replied we didn't need a social worker and that that wasn't her department and I needed to follow up with my child's pediatrician.  The ER doctor's name who told us it was a "normal" reaction was  MD. I had a scheduled visit with my daughter's pediatrician on June 3rd already so I used that appt to also discuss my concerns with getting any more vaccines, especially the MMR. I went back to the ER the following week because the symptoms were still happening.  My arm was still painful, had a rash but did not see the rash. I also developed a bruise on the inside of my arm. It was also tender to the touch and there was so much pressure in my neck and back. I went completely numb over my whole body. I had another visit with my doctor, and she advised that I should go to see a neurologist. My swelling never goes completely down. The neurologist had me do an EKG; it did not conclude anything. I also been doing physical therapy. They are doing an electric stimulus to try to make my muscle relax. It was got to the point where I have muscle spasms in my neck and my vision is still distorted. Term 4-mo female infant presented to ED 6/9/21 with 1 day history of motor weakness.  ~ 2 weeks ago she had mild URI symptoms (cough) for only a couple of days and recovered to baseline.  On  6/7 she received her 4-mo old vaccine series without acute side effects.  She passed stool that day that was more smelly than usual with green tinge. The following day 6/8 AM she appeared generally well, several sneezes produced green mucous and her eye lids were slightly puffy.  She was sent to daycare as usual.  In the afternoon when dad picked her up she appeared ill with eye lids being puffy, poor head control.  She only ate 2 out of 4 bottles during the day, 4 being her usual feeds while at daycare.  When dad attempted to bottle her she had trouble latching on and milk was running out the corner of her mouth.  Through out the evening she progressively became weaker with decreased limb movements.     She presented to local ED overnight and was noted to have temp of 36.1F, RR 24 sating 99% on RA.  She was noted to be lethargic and hypotonic.  There was concern for sepsis/meningitis.  She received 20 mL/kg IVF bolus.  Her glucose was 89.  She had a urinalysis which showed 1+ ketones but was otherwise reassuring.  Her rapid influenza/SARS-CoV-2/RSV was negative.  White blood cell count 8.2 (43% neutrophils, 47% lymphocytes), hematocrit 33.9, platelets 343.  Sodium 138, potassium 4.2, chloride 105, bicarb 21, BUN 9, creatinine less than 0.2, AST 22, ALT 14.  Lumbar puncture demonstrated WBC count of 4, RBC 4, glucose 57, protein 125.  CSF Gram stain did not show any organisms.  Sterile CSF culture. Chest x-ray was normal.  The patient was noted to have an apneic event with an associated desaturation and was placed on 6 L HFNC. She was subsequently transferred to  Hospital PICU for further evaluation and management.  Upon arrival she continued to have worsening respiratory status necessitating intubation.  Per parents there had been no fever, N/V/D.  She feeds breast milk and formula, no solids, no honey, no soil/dirt exposure. There's no family history of neuromuscular disorder.  Baby remains intubated on mechanical ventilation in PICU
LAB_DATA: Stool test negative for botulism. Anti GQ1B Ab negative. MEDICATIONS:  1. S/p BabyBIG 6/10 2. S/p IVIG 2g/kg 6/11-6/15 Rapidly progressive motor weakness with respiratory failure as the admitting Dx, parents report more movements in the past 48 hours.   Compared to physical exam one week ago, there has been small but demonstrable improvement in motor function, now with some limited spontaneous movements.  Although previous clinical history and course appeared most consistent with infantile botulism, no clear exposure ever identified and now stool study negative.  Although age of presentation and descending paralysis less typical for demyelinating process such as Guillain-Barr� syndrome, the cytoalbumin disassociation on CSF studies and nerve root enhancement more consistent with this process.  Anti-GQ 1B antibody which is positive in a subset of Miller Fisher variant Guillain-Barr� syndrome and other similar demyelinating conditions with cranial nerve involvement was also negative, but certainly does not rule out Guillain-Barr� syndrome as potential etiology of her weakness.  I am very pleased that she has started to show some, albeit modest, recovery of motor movement.  Given negative stool study for botulism, would recommend repeat imaging of MRI brain with and without contrast with dedicated cuts through the IACs and brainstem, as well as MRI of total spine to assess for any evolution in prior findings.  Would also revisit the option of obtaining EMG and nerve conduction studies.  Continue supportive care.  Neurology will continue to follow.
OTHER_MEDS: Famotidine for gastroesophageal reflux of infancy

While I was collecting pts history said he didn?t want to talk about it anymore in an attempt to calm himself down, approximately 2-3 minutes later I witnessed pt have another syncopal episode which lasted 15-20 seconds while in seated position. Pt regained consciousness and I had an employee help me move pt to the floor for recovery. Pt displayed no signs of respiratory distress, denied chest pain and headache. Pt states syncope is his typical response after vaccinations or blood draws, last occurrence was 8 months ago during a blood draw. Pt states these syncopal episodes initially started in childhood and has gotten worse as he has gotten older, pts father also experiences these episodes. Pt declined EMS several times. Pt was monitored for 41 minutes, vitals taken twice while pt was in recovery on the floor, vitals were stable. I had pt lay supine on the floor for approximately 15 mins post syncopal episode. After recovering for 15 mins I had patient sit upright on the floor, reassessed him and repeated vitals which were stable, pt reported feeling well. After approximately 10 mins pt was helped up into a seat, vitals were stable and patient reported feeling well and having no complaints. I had pt stand and repeated vitals which continued to be stable and pt reported no complaints. Pt drove to the vaccination site in a rental care which he states he will leave parked close to vaccination site and initially states he?d walk. I recommended pt and girlfriend take a free ride home which the agreed to do. I personally walked the patient up the stairs which pt was able to do with no problem and no reported complaints. Pt was given strict ER precautions and given resources for primary care also. Pt stable at the time of discharge. Pt declined follow up.  Pt stable at the time of discharge. Pt accompanied by with girlfriend, who will get pt home via ride.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The three days after I received my vaccine, I experienced flu like symptoms and a severe headache. The flu like symptoms went away, but the headache did not. On day six, I started to have double vision and I went to the ER because of that. At the ER, (05/15), they kept me all day. They ran a lot of tests. They took me through a "stroke" protocol. They performed a non-contrast CT scan, drew blood work and then they admitted me. I was put on a neurological floor. I had another non-contrast CT, a contrast CT scan, non-contrast MRI, a contrast MRI, a doppler to check my veins for blockages, I was checked for autoimmune diseases and a bubble test. I was told I had high blood pressure. I was given medication for that. I was at 169/97. By the time I was released, it had come down to 139/84. As of today, my blood pressure is normal. I'm still experiencing double vision from time to time. I have to wear a patch on one of my eyes and alternate every 4-6 hours. Right now, I have monocular vision and I'm having to do this until it resolves. I had an ophthalmological assessment and I was sent to a neurological consult with another ophthalmologist. I went to the eye care doctor, with Dr. (Name) (05/25), and she told me that I have a cranial line stick nerve palsy. My right eye is not moving the way it should. It's like it's frozen in place. That is where my blurred vision comes from. My vision is cris-crossing and that is where the double vision is coming from. I have a follow-up appointment on June 29th to see if the patch is working. It was close enough to the vaccination to make me question that it was from the vaccine. With this I have to wait it out for the next six months.
LAB_DATA: I had 2 non-contrast CT scans, a contrast CT scan, blood work done, non-contrast MRI and a contrast MRI, a doppler to check my veins for blockages, a bubble test (putting solution inside to see if there are any bubbles) and they checked for autoimmune diseases.
OTHER_MEDS: I was taking biotin, B-complex and vitamin C.
CUR_ILL: I did not have any other illnesses.
HISTORY: I do not have any chronic or long-standing health conditions.
ALLERGIES: I am allergic to penicillin, erythromycin, all sulfa drugs. I have had reactions to hops (to beer), pineapple and dairy type products.

I vaccinated the patient with Janssen Covid 19 vaccine (as patient requested). He was sitting in the observation area when I looked up and noticed the patient looking pale. This was less than 2 minutes after being immunized. As I headed out the pharmacy to check on the patient, he slid out of his chair and I heard his glasses hit the floor. He was unconscious on his stomach, so I rolled him over to his left side. He immediately regained consciousness and tried to get up. I elevated the patient's feet on a chair while he laid with his back on the floor. The pharmacy technician and another associate called EMS.  Patient was cognizant after 5-7 minutes and answering questions appropriately. When EMS arrived 10 -12 minutes later, patient was laughing and joking with them. Patient has a needle phobia, of which I was aware. Patient was pleasant and appropriate when he while he was being vaccinated, which is why I believe this is a reaction to the vaccine and not from his needle phobia. EMS evaluated the patient and he signed a waiver stating he did not want to go to the hospital. He was instructed not to drive (his companion would drive them home) and to drink lots of water, which he did before leaving. He laughed and joke with myself and the EMS and thanked us numerous times for our care and concern. The whole event lasted about 18 minutes, from patient being vaccinated to leaving with his companion who agreed to drive him home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Timeline: 4/22: Pfizer Dose 2 Covid Vaccine; 5/11: L wrist dropped and numb, all L fingers unable to lift and numb; 5/14: toes burning (felt on fire) and itching, legs felt odd w/ pins and needles spasms and cramps; 5/17: became aware of lack of sensation in legs/feet at physician office; 5/20: ER visit b/c R fingers paralysis began and lightheaded--scared. MRI's performed--no tumors or lesions from notes; 5/24: EMG. Nothing notable. Too soon as Neuro indicated. Neuro Disinterested in anything other than left arm as I expressed; 6/3: Consult with. Last communication as follows: 6/11/2021: Hi mam,  I would not do it earlier than the last week of June for a more accurate study. Also, in regards to the vaccination- unfortunately, there is no way to confirm whether it definitely did or didn't play a role, but you may be right and that it is part of this picture for you. Unfortunately, we are at a place right now where the medical community is still learning about the potential side effects since it is a new vaccination. We don't yet know exactly how long after the vaccination we can expect side effects to occur and how long they are expected to last. The good news is that it doesn't alter your treatment course either way. The same holds true for those that suffer from headaches after the vaccination or even covid-19 infection. The headaches are treated the same as regular tension headaches/migraines. If there is a component of a vaccine side effect we do expect time to help heal that as well, but I would definitely continue with our plan to proceed with the nerve study, PT, and avoiding positions that cause nerve compression.    Sincerely, PA-C   On 6/7/2021 Physician also wrote: Guillain Barre Syndrome can happen after vaccinations and is something that I did consider for you. I do not think that your symptoms and exam align too well with it though. The "text book" or "hallmark" presentation is ascending weakness, numbness, and tingling. It typically starts in the feet and can work its way all the way up to the hands and respiratory muscles. The pattern of your symptoms is not quite consistent with this.
LAB_DATA: 5/20: ER visit b/c R fingers paralysis began and lightheaded--scared. MRI's performed--no tumors or lesions from notes; 5/24: EMG. 6/3: appointment with Neuro

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had her second covid vaccine on 6/2/21 and had a lot of gi symptoms (like bloating and gas and feeling hungry even though she had eaten).  Then she suddenly had the pancreatitis on 6/8/21.  She had never had any issues with her gallbladder prior.  Pt ended up having cholecystectomy.  Patient is currently recovering.
LAB_DATA: her gallbladder only had sludge and a few very small stones.  no stone was found on ercp and it was thought perhaps she passed a stone.   MRI cholangiopacreatogram 6/10/21 1. Mild layering sludge and stones within the gallbladder  2. No evidence of gallbladder wall thickening  3. Borderline prominence of the common bile duct measuring 6 mm with rapid distal tapering. A definite filling defect is not seen to suggest choledocholithiasis on this examination. Some image motion degradation is present.  Findings may represent stigmata of a recently passed common bile duct stone. Follow-up may include a HIDA scan if indicated clinically versus a repeat MRCP after an appropriate interval of 2-3 weeks  CT abdomen and pelvis with contrast (6/8/21) Layering tiny gallbladder calculi versus hyperdense sludge.  Mild extrahepatic biliary dilatation possibly related to biliary calculi which may have passed.  Consider MRCP particularly if bilirubin increases.  Subcentimeter low-attenuation adrenal nodule, most likely an adenoma, not requiring follow-up per ACR recommendations.  Remainder of exam unremarkable without other findings to suggest etiology for pain.  US abdomen complete (6/8/21) 1. Mildly prominent common bile duct, choledocholithiasis cannot be excluded. 2. Fatty infiltration of liver.

I got Johnson & Johnson ?Janssen? on May 3. For reference, I have moderate to severe ME/CFS and vestibular migraine. I had COVID in December, was bedridden for two months, and almost recovered to baseline before the jab. Here?s my V timeline:  Day 1: May 3   Several mins after J&J: Huge hot flash and vertigo spin that went away immediately   30 mins after: Felt drunk  Rest of evening: Extra sleepy  Day 2-3:  Extra dizziness and fatigue, mostly in bed. Definitely felt like I was fighting something.  Day 4: Vertigo attack.  Days 5-11: Felt better than I had since before having COVID! Less dizziness, more energy. My post-Covid symptoms such as orthostasis had greatly improved.? My resting heart rate was sometimes in the 70s!?  Day 12: ADVERSE EVENT: I felt like I got COVID all over again, but less severe. Nevertheless, my feeling of breathlessness was enough to send me to urgent care. I also had chest pain/heaviness, extra dizziness, and increased heart rate (117 resting). EKG at urgent care showed abnormalities similar to EKG I had in December when I first had Covid. So, I ended up in the emergency room. No clot or heart blockage. Doctor seemed to think either I was having a delayed reaction to the vaccine, or this was somehow Covid related.???  Day 13: Woke up feeling better until I had breakfast and had to poop. After doing that, I got so exhausted I landed back in bed all afternoon. This was another problem I had during Covid.? At least my resting heart rate was more normal, 98.  Day 14: ??Vertigo kicks in on top of everything else. Xanax is the only thing that helps my vertigo so I took that and was in bed all day.  Day 15: Didn?t sleep well but a little better.  Day 16: Chest pain and breathlessness are worse again. They got worse after I took a shower upon waking up.???  Day 51 (Today, 6/22/21): Chest pain and breathlessness are much better. Still have extra dizziness. Resting heart rate is usually between 88-100 now. Orthostasis has improved but not gone.
LAB_DATA: 5/14: EKG: Sinus tachycardia. ST and T wave abnormality, consider inferior ischemia. T wave inversion now evident in Inferior leads. Nonspecific T wave abnormality now in Lateral leads. 5/14: SARS-COV-2: Negative 5/14: CT scan chest: normal, no embolism or cardiopulmonary disease 5/14: CBC: Potassium low, Magnesium low. WBC count high  5/14: Troponin normal 5/25: Normal ECG

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received 1st injection on lunch break around noon.   Went back to work and a few hours later I felt light pressure on left side beneath left breast.  The pressure became worse and felt tight.  It became hard to breathe. I kept trying to take breaths but could not get enough air. It was frightening so I went and told one of the doctors I work with what I was feeling.  He told another doctor.  They both told me I may be experiencing anxiety as I wouldn?t be able to feel reactions from the vaccination so soon.   I can?t tell you exactly how long this tight/pressure hard-to-breathe feeling lasted but it was enough to make me lightheaded.  It was enough to make me call the number on the Pfizer booklet they gave me but the number took me to a hotline and it was confusing and there wasn?t a clear option to talk to someone to tell them what I was experiencing.  I also had to continue working.    I was so happy when my chest started to gradually feel less pressure.  Then breathing became easier.   I was tired after I went home and experienced soreness at the site of injection after approXimately 5 pm.  This was serious and now that I had a abnormal EKG and am scheduled for an echocardiogram, makes me wonder if what I felt was due to the vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Admitted on 6/18 with fever, pain at injection site and chest pain. Evaluated at local ED, found to have an elevated troponin to 12 and ST elevation in anterolat leads by report  on EKG. An ECHO was obtained and revealed decreased EF to 47% and he was transferred to our hospital,  initially monitored with telemetry, troponin levels every 6 hours and started on scheduled ibuprofen.  Troponin peaked at 22.82 first hospital night on 6/18, then down-trending. Telemetry was without any ectopy. Symptoms improved and hemodynamically stable throughout his PICU course.  Transferred to the pediatric floor on 6/19, continued to do well. Discharged on 6/20 with troponin of 5.92 ng/mL and EF of 55-60% on ECHO.

I have neurological issues since the shot. I have trouble with concentration, problem solving activities, reading, listening in conversation, and fast-paced or complicated computer work. What happens is that I feel my brain not keeping up, lagging, drifting. It's like waves of exhaustion. Things have improved a lot for me, however there are still times when I struggle. I had high blood pressure that wouldn't settle down after the shot. I ham now on blood pressure medication and a statin for high cholesterol. I also have hearing loss and vertigo. Vertigo is every day when I go to bed. I had pain in my ears off and on since the shot. According to the audiologist, the hearing impairment is moderate but presents difficulty with particular consonants during normal levels of conversation and hearing aids are recommended. There was one test that was given during the exam where I became dizzy. The audiologist said she had never seen the result before. My plan is to have another hearing test in late July in case something might improve. The ear pain has subsided, with a sharp pain in the ear now and again, but rarely these days. Not experiencing strange sounds (crunching, or piercing high notes) like before. Although hearing loss has been verified, I believe that the problems I have had with conversation involve both hearing loss and cognition. There is problem solving involved with engaging conversation. I get dizzy, like waves of exhaustion in my mind when I'm having trouble with conversation. Thankfully this problem is much improved but it does still happen. I will now paste in a log I was keeping in case the dates, etc., are helpful.   March 19, 2021 Since learning yesterday that my antibody test result for Covid-19 is negative, I want to document what I have experienced since receiving the Pfizer vaccine on March 8th, 2021.   I am a 62-year-old female who is healthy, although somewhat overweight who has had uncontrolled high blood pressure off and on in the past. I also have osteoarthritis and a history of migraines. I experienced neurological symptoms and other symptoms after receiving the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine for Covid-19 on March 8th. These included dizziness, flushes of heat, chills, vertigo, elevated blood pressure, tingling on the right side of my face, cloudiness in cognition, zingy nerve sensations all across my brain and waves of "exhaustion" (like waves in the mind, like being adrift) when using the computer (typing, proofing typed work, reading dense documents, working with excel files, working with email)�and difficulty with conversation (marked difficulty with listening), and trouble with reading.  After receiving the vaccine at around 10:45 in the morning at a pharmacy, I soon felt dizzy and quite warm during the waiting period. I removed my jacket, scarf and baseball cap; someone nearby fetched me a water bottle. After 10 minutes passed, I knew I shouldn't leave at the 15-minute mark because making my way to the window to pick up the vaccine card was not possible right then. I stayed for 30, informed the pharmacist that I was very hot and dizzy. She said she felt it was my immune response. I went to my car and cooled off there with the air conditioner. Eventually, after about 15 more minutes, I drove myself a short distance home.   Back at home it was lunch time and I had some trouble putting the lunch together. I was confused. I put something in the microwave, forgot what it was, heard the dinging and checked. It was a bowl of soup I forgot I was warming. It was only 2 inches of broth/sauce, though, and the other ingredients that go in it were in front of me still cold on the wood board. At that point, I was startled that I was having this confusion, I knew my mind was not working as normal but figured it would pass with rest, and thought that my vaccine and immune response were probably overwhelming my mind. I went to bed and felt my mind was very zingy with nerve twinges, like when you can feel nerve activity/healing going on in your body, and I slept for about three hours. I was groggy upon awakening.  I knew I had a high blood pressure issue that wasn't abating after the vaccine. Admittedly I was amped up when I went to the pharmacy get the vaccine and I'm pretty sure I had elevated blood pressure when I received the vaccine. I had tossed and turned, hadn't slept well the night before. I was scared and worried. My body's immune system is what I would call overactive and I was afraid of the response. (Not sure overactive is the right word, but my immune system protects me fiercely. I would say my immune response is intense.) Although I was afraid to get the vaccine, I wanted the benefits and knew I needed the protection.   The next thing that became apparent was a problem with conversation. I found I could not do the normal back and forth of talking and listening with my husband. I could make words and sentences, short ones preferably, not involved, but listening was almost impossible. Longer sentences I made were coming out a little slower I noticed, but not by much; they were more considered, I would say. My blood pressure would shoot up during conversation. I would get sensations in my head and feel dizzy and things would start fogging up in there somehow. I felt exhausted by conversation. I would want to run away. And for the next few days, that is exactly what I did. I stayed upstairs in my room, working remotely for my job as best I could, and not talking or listening to anyone.   I bought a blood pressure monitor and began monitoring on March 10th. Here is a table of results.  March 10 6:16 pm 150/63   80   7:10 pm 150/88   74   10:15 pm 130/68   70 After sleep March 11 11:30 am 152/84   70  March 12 7:00 am 154/79   65   9:30 am 176/78   80 On phone with advice nurse. Couldn't get appt. was told to go to Urgent Care March 12 Spent time in Urgent Care and ER. Blood pressure remained elevated.  Was told to follow up with primary care doctor for blood pressure, to make decision on meds. March 13 9:00 am 152/72   72   3:00 pm 151/75   84   5:30 pm 140/72   88   9:00 pm 145/82   74  March 14 7:00 am 150/79   66   9:30 am 157/98   79   3:38 pm 146/66   85   8:35 pm 156/72   73  March 15 7:25 am 151/78   67   10:15 am 157/70   62   1:45 pm 156/70   73   3:30 pm 178/78   96 At doctor visit. Was prescribed Cozaar 12.5 mg/day March 16 Midnight 145/72   71   6:30 am 141/80   66   8:00 am 148/82   91   3:30 pm 140/78   86   8:13 pm 134/71   73  March 17 7:30 am 128/76   67   6:00 pm 132/75   76  March 18 10:30 am 130/90   83 Ate at 10:00 am  8:45 pm 137/79   78  March 19 10:00 am 133/83   89    Over the course of this experience, I have been flushing with heat, beginning at the pharmacy. Perhaps pure high blood pressure effects, I don't know those things. I want to mention it because I do not normally flush with heat like that. On the evenings of March 13th and 14th, I had strong chills at bedtime, literally vibrated into a down coat, slept in it and many blankets. On March 12th, when moving in and out, etc., of the CT scanner at the ER, I had vertigo. I had no idea when it was over, that it had stopped, until they helped me up. I have had vertigo for about 4 nights upon going to sleep. I may have had more vertigo during this experience, but with the dizzy, I'm not sure. I began a few days ago to want very cold temperatures at night and I left my slider and my window open for sleep and enjoyed it during a 40-degree night. When I wash my hair, I'm sitting in a warm bath but I rinse my head with cold water. It feels great. And right, somehow. Warm water is not the thing for me right now, head-wise.   Neurological issues continue. I have to read somewhat slower. Reading something complex is several reads, even if just a few sentences. I have stopped on the novel I was reading. I have to type somewhat slower. Typing takes a lot out of me, much more so than usual; I have zings in my head all over sometimes when I'm writing on the computer, when I'm re-reading my writing, working, emailing, and just in general when I try to do too much on the computer. I find excel files to be overwhelming with the data everywhere and me zipping around them for my work. Luckily, I don't have an excel project going on at the moment. Right now, I would say my computer time in general has to be broken up with breaks. I never had to take breaks before when I was involved/trying to meet a deadline/ working on something. I take short walks in nature, go outside on my patio to enjoy the birds, play with my dog, when the computer has been too much for me.   Finally, I must tell you that I have a lot going on in my mind at this point in my life. I am grieving. I am peri-menopausal. My mother (82) fell and hurt herself in November and had a light stroke about three weeks ago.    April 7, 2021 As of now, I am still having neurological issues but things are much better than before. I am able to write and read and do my work on the computer for the most part. If I try to speed along, I might need to take a break, but mostly I am able to work. When it comes to excel sheets with a lot of data to manage and move around, I'm not there yet. It's overwhelming.   I am left with trouble with listening as my major complaint. What happens when I have to focus intently on listening is that I feel my brain sort of quake or drift. I have to walk away from what I'm doing to calm down this ill feeling.   April 11, 2021 I had a hard time with the quake/drift last night. I was awake at 2:30 am. (This is a fairly normal thing for me to be up in the night writing, reading or whatever; it's something I do quite a bit.) I tried to do a couple of sentences on the computer and I noticed right away that it wasn't going as it should. The two days prior, I had no drift and was feeling so hopeful. Last night I felt like I did back when this problem was at its worst. I had to stop. I had a lot of vertigo. I propped myself up on the bed at various degrees to find a good spot. I had a hard time. I meditated and apparently fell asleep; I awoke to being in a seated position, head hanging. I then tried to lay down and sleep, nope, more vertigo. I tried to meditate again and woke up the same way again. Well, finally it subsided. This morning I was not myself in terms of cognition, thinking. I was just kind of off. Maybe I was worried, this setback made me worry about my future. An awful feeling.   Some History I've gone over a few things in my mind that I want to share. One is that early on in the Pandemic, I believe I was exposed to the virus via a co-worker who had been very sick with an infection and returned to work with a terrible cough. She had had an interaction with a woman affiliated. I cannot confirm if my co-worker had Covid-19 but she told me she suspected she may and that she was considering getting tested.   In March of 2020, I had a terrible rash, red eyes and lids and red toes. The rash was like swaths of raised, red areas that felt hot and itchy like hives�they were large patches, these huge areas on my body, like continents, that migrated/moved across my body. My groin was affected as were my armpits. They were hot and itchy. In the records you will find a phone appointment where I discussed my extensive rash. There is also a phone appointment where I discussed a very sore throat that would not relent. I believe I may have had MIS-A and my lymph glands (tonsils?) in my throat were very painful and swollen. I continued to have problems with my throat for a year. Sometimes I would have broth rather than food, it was so hard to swallow. Other times it was not as bad. The soreness, difficulty swallowing was constant but to varying degrees.   After I had the Pfizer shot, I felt the glands in my throat finally release. That was a relief to me. I felt some strange sensations on the day of the Pfizer shot. I felt a lot of activity in my brain that was very frightening. A lot of activity, electricity, nerves. I felt a sharp shard (felt like a tiny spike or piece of glass, miniscule) pass through one eye, and then the other; through one ear, and then the other; through one breast, and then the other. Both knees, both shoulders and my wrist where I had carpal tunnel surgery flared some although that passed fairly quickly.   The glands in my throat (my tonsils?) are doing so much better. This is a relief because it was a difficult problem for which I had no solution. I was gargling with mouthwash, with salt water, and using cough drops. Sometimes, with the mask-wearing in the supermarket, it was very difficult to breathe. My plan was to get vaccinated and then ask for a referral to get the throat scoped to make sure I didn't have a serious problem there.  I have had pain in my ears off and on since the shot. I wonder if the problem I am having with focus on the language of others (listening/conversation) has to do with something that happened in my ears. I attended a meeting for my work on March 29th and I was unable to manage. I was, of course, trying to listen carefully to the speakers but it was overwhelming for me. My mind was not able to deal with listening, concentrating, paying attention. I sat silent and still, not commenting and left at the end of 35 minutes.  April 20, 2021 I was able to have a conversation on the phone with my mother for over an hour. This was the first time since March 8th.  I felt good about it. There were other positives last week with my mind and cognition and how I was doing with my work. But, yesterday, April 19th, I found myself almost unable to work effectively most of the day. I tried this and that and my mind was just drifting. It's a very unsettling feeling, like vertigo inside and I find I cannot accomplish much because I cannot trust myself and have to check and re-check things. (I was working on paying some speakers we had to compensate for their time.) The day proceeded like this until I gave up around 4:30. An awful feeling to be ineffective. Today, I had a visit from my grandchildren and so I was very little on the computer. Just here and there. I find my mind still was rocking around some.   Later, in the nighttime I believe the brain itself was actually shaking. I am not sure, since it was night and I was unable to quite figure out what the sensation was. I was scared, since it was something I had not experienced before. I have also noticed in recent days that my head will "itch", not really itch, but it is tingly on the inside and I find I touch my head on the outside as if it were an itch I could scratch. It isn't unpleasant like an itch, it's more like when your hair moves�but the feeling is inside.   I am troubled about my future at work. My work is mentally demanding. I work with numbers, schedules of classes, data�plus students and professors. I help with translation, I edit and proof academic writing. My work also requires strong interpersonal skills. Listening difficulty is a major thing when it comes to meetings with colleagues.

The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.    Co-suspect product included non-company product DUPILUMAB (DUPIXENT) injection for Atopic dermatitis. Concomitant products included DIPHENHYDRAMINE HYDROCHLORIDE (BENADRYL [DIPHENHYDRAMINE HYDROCHLORIDE]) for Sleep disorder, HYDROCORTISONE ACETATE (HYDROCORT [HYDROCORTISONE ACETATE]) for an unknown indication.   On 04-May-2021, the patient started DUPILUMAB (DUPIXENT) (Subcutaneous) 600 mg once. On 20-May-2021, the patient went to emergency room due to abdominal pain and was noted to have kidney stones. A 34-years-old non-pregnant female patient received second dose of BNT162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 mRNA VACCINE, Formulation: Solution for injection, Batch/Lot number: EM9810), via an unspecified route of administration in right arm on 10Feb2021 11:30 AM (at the age of 34-years-old) as a single dose for COVID-19 immunisation at the hospital. Medical history included supraventricular tachycardia with unknown reasons of causing the rapid heart rate. The patient had no allergies. Concomitant medication included (other medications in two weeks) sertraline taken for an unspecified indication, start and stop date were not reported. The patient previously took first dose of BNT162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 mRNA VACCINE, Formulation: Solution for injection, Batch/Lot number: EL8982), via an unspecified route of administration in right arm on 20Jan2021 12:00 PM (at the age of 34-years-old) for COVID-19 immunisation. No other vaccinations in 4 weeks. No COVID prior vaccination. Tested for COVID-19 post vaccination with negative result. On 11Feb2021 01:00, the patient experienced SVT (supraventricular tachycardia), woke up about 1 am with a rapid heart rate and pain in her chest/ heart rate was measured at 240bpm, trouble catching her breath. The patient stated that the night of 10Feb2021, she felt asleep symptom free. She woke up about 1am with a rapid heart rate and pain in her chest. She got out of bed to use the techniques to bring the heart rate down on her own. Unfortunately, she was unsuccessful. After almost 30 minutes she made her way to the ER due to pain in my chest, and trouble catching my breath due to me starting to become afraid of the rapid heart rate. Upon arriving my heart rate was measured at 240bpm. The SVT was resolved with Adenosine. She wanted to point out this was the first time waking to the rapid heart rate and the first time experiencing pain in her chest from it. She normally moving or doing some form of low impact activity when the SVT is triggered, like walking, dancing, She was unaware of how long she experienced the rapid heart rate before waking up. She was not sure if the vaccine contributed to the heart rate but thought it was safer to share. The adverse event was resulted in Emergency room visit. The adverse event was treated with adenosine. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included heart rate: 240bpm on 11Feb2021 and nasal swab COVID test: negative on 10Feb2021. The outcome of events was recovered on an unspecified date in 2021.  Follow-up (10Jun2021): Follow-up attempts are completed. No further information is expected.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Fingers were turning blue; Palms turned bright red; she was diagnosed with Raynaud's; The initial case was missing the following minimum criteria: unspecified adverse event. Upon receipt of follow-up information on 07Jun2021, this case now contains all required information to be considered valid.  This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other healthcare professional (hcp; patient). A 68-years-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE, Solution for injection, Lot Number: EL9266, expiry date not reported) via an unspecified route of administration, administered in left arm on 11Feb2021 (at the age of 68 years old) as second dose, single for covid-19 immunization. Medical history included ongoing allergies; ongoing history of anaphylaxis; deficient in Vitamin D; she had a bad pneumonia and was septic and knocked out her immune system and almost died; had allergies to food, dyes, allergy meds; had hypotension (described as "they're neurally mediated hypotension, dyes, could be smells said certain things like that"); MTHFRA1298 positive (described as "it's kind of like a mutation, says when you're homozygous you usually don't have any issues with clotting or bleeding"); and said that food, the red and yellow dyes bottom out her blood pressure. She said that since that time she had pneumonia as per her history, she has had multiple episodes and since COVID affects lungs and she was an HCP, she didn't want to be working until she could take the vaccine. She stated her niece was travelling and she called her doctor to see what he thinks. The doctor said he can't tell you what to do; it was a month or two after the vaccine. The doctor just wouldn't recommend it and said it was not a good idea. She felt awful. She would like to return to work, but she needed to know the chances of surviving because of her lungs and the pneumonia. She stated that the CDC did an investigation in 2006/2007 about this pneumonia and wondered if it was fungal. The CDC had to investigate, said it knocked out her immune system. She never had allergies until that, dyes like red and yellow, and she has all kinds of allergies after that episode. She was not sure how it affected the immune system: the pneumonia and then allergies to food, dyes, allergy meds. Patient reported history as she carried an epi pen since childhood and said her primary concern was wasps, bees, things like that and she was never without it as food, the red and yellow dyes bottom out her blood pressure. The epi pen primarily affected most of the allergies, they're neurally mediated hypotension, dyes, could be smells, said certain things like that. She knows what do when she feels like she's going to pass out. It's managed and she's doing pretty well. Family medical history included some family is heterozygous and have had bleeding and clotting. She, her twin sister and brothers were all homozygous. Her father has had autoimmune issues like ITP, so his platelets weren't forming, and if there was bleeding he had to be careful. There were no concomitant medications; reported as patient doesn't take any medications. The patient had no prior vaccinations (within 4 weeks) or had not had any other vaccinations within four weeks prior to the first administration date of the suspect vaccine and stated she kept away from vaccines because of previous reactions she's had. The patient received the first dose of bnt162b2 for covid-19 immunisation on 21Jan2021 at maybe between 7-7:30, as she said she got in early  (lot number: EL3248), administered in the left arm, and within 24-48 hours after her first injection she had shingles. She also experienced couldn't feel some of her toes; and when she took her shoes off, the toes she couldn't feel were totally white. Patient stated that she was worried and almost didn't get the second dose. She treated the shingles on her own, and said it wasn't so much the burning but was more the itching and blisters all over her back. She used a home remedy of toothpaste for the shingles, and it dried it out and stopped the itching. The shingles were annoying, and her shirt was soaking wet from the blisters; it was awful, but not really disabling. She said that if she went out, she just had to make sure her shirt didn't get soaking we; it was annoying. She didn't go to the hospital because she knew what it was. Patient previously took epinephrine (EPIPEN) since childhood for allergies; and had intermittently took vitamin D for she periodically was really deficient in Vitamin D. On the first dose, she started noticing she couldn't feel some of her toes, and said when she took her shoes off, the toes she couldn't feel were totally white. She had never had that happen before, and she questioned if she should get the second dose or not. She then went and got it. She then started noticing her feet and fingers, her fingers were turning blue and she has pictures of that, too. She had been plagued with this since she got it, she's not saying it's from the vaccine, not 100 percent, but she's never had it and she does now. Her palms turned bright red and all of a sudden, her fingers turned blue on an unspecified date in 2021. She was diagnosed with Raynaud's in 2021, and no one in her family has had it and she has never had it herself. Patient stated that she got the vaccine at the same time as the first (between 7am to 730 am). Her fingers started after the second dose; it might have started before, but she thinks it was after the second dose. Patient stated that she would really like to see if she has any antibodies; she wondered did she mount any kind of response. The events required physician office visit as she visited the doctor due to the toe and finger discoloration, and said it took a couple of months to get an appointment because it was a specialist. The events were reported as serious medically significant but said were not disabling and she went to the doctor. Patient stated that her blood platelets have been fine and both hemoglobin and hematocrit were fine on an unknown date. She doesn't have a PCP, just shows up and does a general, from mammogram to PAP (dates unknown; unknown results), and said it's just a general visit. The outcome of the events was unknown. Patient stated that events reported were related to Pfizer COVID vaccine. Reported said that there was a strong possibility it's correlated, and said that when you look at the time frame and the time period, the fact that it was never there and now it is. The correlation is pretty strong. She never did anything for shingles and said she never had the vaccine.

This contactable nurse reported for 63-year-old male patient (reporter's husband)  A 63-year-old male patient received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, solution for injection: Lot number: EWO709), via an unspecified route of administration on 17May2021 as a single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Historical vaccine included Hepatitis B vaccine. The patient's medical history included allergy, fatty liver, weight loss, Irritation of Nasopharynx, Granuloma (//2020). The caller stated that on May/2021, about less than 2 weeks after receiving the first dose, the patient started to feel very tired and his O2 saturation while resting was 90-93 on room air and with deep breathing he reached 95, but while he was laying down and sleeping it drops below 90. The reporter stated that the patient had no fever and no inflammation except a little itching at the injection site. The reporter also stated that the patient was excessively tired and sleeps every day. Stated that they didn't really pay attention to when tiredness started, but it was around the last week of May. The reporter stated that they had a weight trainer who comes to the house. The patient stated that her husband felt exhausted during the weight training and couldn't do his workout. Caller stated that she has tried to associate it with other things, the low 02 sat and said that it could be something else. It was reported that he has no coughing and no shortness of breath. It was stated that on 27May2021, her husband was really pooped. The reporter stated that she had him walked with the Pulse Ox and they went outside and had him run a little bit and do a little bit of cardio and his heart rate went up to. Caller stated that he was tachy and it stayed for a day after he ran and stated that it was after he ran in the evening and through the following day. Caller stated that he took some Raw Garlic because it helped when he was tachy before. Caller stated that her husband didn't directly complain of the arm side effects, it was more of her asking whether he was having any side effects, and he said just a little itch, no redness or swelling. The reporter stated that he was laughing about the shot, and had no body aches or tears, just itching on the deltoid area for just a few days and as time progressed, he started to feel more tired. Caller stated that the Low O2 Saturation has improved. Caller stated that she had him do the incentive spirometry and it was gradually starting to go up. Caller stated that they haven't checked his sleep tracking devices yet. Caller stated that on the same arm he wears a Garmin and a Fit Bit to make sure he was not going crazy. Caller stated that at night his O2 saturation level dropped to 88 for long periods of time. Caller stated that they ordered a Garmin night sleep tracking device from, towards the first of June. Caller stated that she was checking him with 2 pulse oximeters and then she ordered the Garmin on 01Jun2021. The reporter stated that low O2 saturation started towards the end of May, may be on 28-31 May. The patient had a physician office visit due to the events. Caller stated that they have postponed his second dose until they see what was going on and they wanted to improve his 02 saturation. Caller stated that the patient was able to walk 5 miles 2-3 times a week and did swimming. Caller stated that the patient was concerned about his low 02 saturation. Caller wanted to report this and the doctors did not know what to do with the second vaccine. Caller stated that it will be 35 days this coming (Monday) since his first vaccine. Caller was asking whether the low 02 Saturation can be a side effect of the vaccine. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included CT and pulmonary tests done with normal results. The patient o2 saturation level tests with unspecified results. The reporter assessed the events to be related with the suspect product. The outcome of the events was not resolved for fatigue, oxygen saturation decreased, unknown for 35 days this coming Monday since his first vaccine and resolved for other events.  Follow-up (17Jun2021)- Follow-up information was received from the same contactable nurse included non-clinical information  Information on Lot/Batch number was available. Additional information has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on temporal association, the causal relationship between BNT162B2 and the events cannot be excluded. SYMPTOM_TEXT: passed out (head flew back)/her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds and then they called EMS; HA/Headache; nausea; dizziness; elevated BP; This is a spontaneous report received from a contactable nurse from Pfizer sponsored program. This is first of three report. An 18-years-old female patient received second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTEC COVID-19 VACCINE, Solution for injection, Lot Number: ER8727; Expiry Date: 31Jul2021), via an unspecified route of administration on 17Jun2021 (at the age of 18-years-old) as a single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. Patient had previously received first dose of BNT162B2 on an unknown date for COVID-19 immunisation and had no reaction. On 17Jun2021, patient experienced passed out (head flew back)/ her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds and then they called EMS and had HA/ headache, nausea, dizziness and elevated BP. About 10 minutes after the injection, patient started complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness. She got to the point where she had appeared to pass out when she was sitting. The observation nurse was with her when she had complained of the headache, nausea and being dizzy and then her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds. After that 10 seconds she was responsive again but she was still complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness until the EMS arrived. Reporter stated that they have been administering this particular lot number at that location for about 2 weeks now without any incidents until today all of a sudden. 2 of the patient's reactions were kind of typical reactions that they have seen in the past. No further details provided about reactions in the past. The other one (reported in report 1 of 3) that had to be treated with an epinephrine (EPIPEN) was a pretty significant reaction and they have never had multiple reactions back to back like this. Reporter seriousness for events, her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds and then they called EMS, complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness were reported as not serious. Verbatim event relatedness: COVID vaccine: her head went back to where she appeared to of lost consciousness for about 10 seconds, complaining of a headache, nausea and dizziness were unrelated. Seriousness: She would even call it a mild to moderate reaction. She thinks that she would of been fine without medical intervention. She was okay during the time in observation without actual medical intervention other than helping to calm her down and that type of thing. Causality: She doesn't think the COVID vaccine caused the reaction necessarily. She thinks it may of been anxiety induced symptoms. The outcome for events headache was unknown and for other events was recovering. Information on Lot/Batch number was available. Additional information has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on known drug safety profile and temporal relationship, there is reasonable possibility of causal association between the event Loss of consciousness, Headache, nausea, Dizziness, Elevated BP  and the suspect drug BNT162B2.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.
